          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The asymmetrical multiplayer genre is a class of games that is very difficult to get right. The most notable success is ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Dead by Daylight",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " which has enjoyed a faithful playerbase for all of its life so far, but others might also think of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Friday the 13th: The Game",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ". However, examples like ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Evolve",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " come to mind when thinking about the failures of the genre. Needless to say, it’s a fun genre of games that can be easy to mess up. Enter the most recent addition to the genre, ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Dragon Ball: The Breakers",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", developed by Dimps and published by Bandai Namco. Players on the surviving team take control of ordinary citizens as they attempt to survive the world-ending power of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Dragon Ball Z",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "’s biggest villains, scrambling to find a way to start a time machine and escape. The player on the villain’s side can take control of Freiza, Cell, or Majin Buu as they grow in power, change forms, and attempt to kill the enemy team. On its face, it is a very fresh spin on the ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Dragon Ball",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " video game formula, one that doesn’t worship the ground that Goku walks on at every opportunity.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
